      <p>ADIEU is the single best vowel-dump word — it uses 4 of your 5 vowels in one play and scores 6 points. If you draw AEIOU with two consonants, ADIEU should be your first thought.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Strategies for Excess Vowels</h2>
      <p>The Scrabble tile bag contains 42 vowels out of 100 total tiles. Drawing 5+ vowels happens more often than you'd expect. Here's how to handle it:</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Play, don't exchange:</span> Exchanging tiles loses your entire turn. Even a low-scoring vowel dump (5-8 points) is usually better than giving your opponent a free turn while you swap.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Memorise 2-letter vowel pairs:</span> AA, AI, OE — these let you play parallel to existing words, scoring points from multiple crossings even with just 2-3 points base value.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Target premium squares:</span> Even a 2-point vowel word scores 4-6 when placed on a double letter/word square. AA on a double word is 4 points plus it opens a hook spot.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Think hooks:</span> Many vowel words can be hooked later — AAL, AAH, AIS, OES. By playing the short word now, you create scoring opportunities for future turns.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

